<%# STUFF #49 — rendered when the inbound request lacks valid
    admin Basic Auth credentials, OR when the user has explicitly
    logged out via POST /admin/logout (`session[:admin_logged_out]`
    is then truthy, set by the before-filter into @admin_logged_out).
    The logged-out variant gets a "Resume admin" link that hits
    GET /admin/login (the one path exempted from the gate); the
    plain-401 variant explains the Basic Auth caveat. %>

<div class="page-header">
  <div>
    <% if @admin_logged_out %>
      <h2>👋 Logged out of admin</h2>
      <p class="subtitle">
        You explicitly logged out, so this session is ignoring the
        browser's cached admin credentials. The credentials prompt
        won't reappear until you click <strong>Resume admin</strong>
        below — entering credentials anywhere else right now would
        just loop back here.
      </p>
      <p>
        <%# data-turbo="false" forces a full browser navigation. Without
            it, Turbo intercepts the click + does an XHR-style fetch, and
            the 401 we get from /admin (after /admin/login clears the
            flag and redirects) doesn't trigger the browser's Basic Auth
            prompt — XHR/fetch 401s don't pop the native prompt. Result
            without this attribute: user stays on this page, looking
            like nothing happened, even though the session flag did
            actually clear. %>
        <a class="btn-primary" href="/admin/login" data-turbo="false">Resume admin &rarr;</a>
        &nbsp;
        <a href="/">Back to home</a>
      </p>
      <p class="subtitle">
        To FULLY clear cached credentials (e.g. before handing the
        browser to someone else), close every tab of this site or use
        a private window. HTTP Basic Auth has no protocol-level logout
        — this is the best browsers offer.
      </p>
    <% else %>
      <h2>🔒 Admin only</h2>
      <p class="subtitle">
        The admin area requires the operator password. If your
        browser didn't show a credentials prompt, your client probably
        doesn't speak HTTP Basic Auth — try again with
        <code>curl -u user:pass</code> or a different browser.
      </p>
      <p>
        &larr; <a href="/">Back to home</a>
      </p>
    <% end %>
  </div>
</div>
